'''Vern T. Miyagi''' was an administrator responsible for the day-to-day operations of the [[Hawaii Emergency Management Agency]] (HI-EMA) from September 11, 2015 to January 30, 2018. Before that he was executive officer at Hawaii EMA. He is a retired [[United States Army]] [[Major general (United States)|major general]] with over 37 years service.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dod.hawaii.gov/hiema/contact-us/about-us/senior-staff-biographies/|title=Hawaii Emergency Management Agency - Leadership|website=dod.hawaii.gov}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalguard.mil/portals/31/Features/ngbgomo/bio/1/1402.html|title=Major General Vern T. Miyagi|website=www.nationalguard.mil}}</ref> In January 2018 he took responsibility for [[2018 Hawaii false missile alert|the false issue of a warning of nuclear attack on Hawaii]] even though it was not him who mistakenly issued the warning.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-01-14/vern-miyagi-apologises-for-sending-missile-warning/9327678|title=Vern Miyagi apologises for sending missile warning in error|date=14 January 2018|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/368912-hawaii-ema-administrator-takes-responsibility-for-false-missile|title=Hawaii EMA administrator takes responsibility for false missile alarm|first=Josh|last=Delk|date=13 January 2018|publisher=}}</ref> He resigned on January 30, 2018, in response to the false alarm. <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2018/01/30/us/hawaii-false-alarm-investigation/index.html|title=Hawaii false missile alert 'button pusher' fired|last=CNN|first=Madison Park, Keith Allen, Lawrence Davidson and Liz Turrell,|work=CNN|access-date=2018-01-30}}</ref>
